[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Java module compilation**\n\nI need to check if the module source indentation in text blocks requires spaces since Java text blocks strip incidental indentation. I wonder about the import order as Checkstyle may expect java imports before org, although existing tests have them reversed. \n\nUsing JavaCompiler with separate module-info and source seems promising, as it compiles correctly. Also, I’m considering if the output directory structure is appropriate and if it’s possible to have duplicate module layers for testing. Overall, I think I’m on the right track!\n\n**Considering Mockito module compatibility**\n\nI'm wondering whether Mockito can mock a class in a module that doesn't read Mockito itself. The module class inherits only from Object, and the generated subclass is in the same context. For non-local scenarios, the generated mock might be under `sample.internal.ModuleType$MockitoMock`, and ByteBuddy is loading it in a multiple parent class loader. Even though the package isn’t exported, the handler could adjust exports after the injection. \n\nI need to be cautious of dynamic access lines, ensuring they run before any failures and also confirming the compiler behavior in a native context.\n\n**Examining compile process and exceptions**\n\nI’m considering the compile process, which may involve dynamic class loading and could throw an `UnsupportedFeatureError`. I need to ensure that my test method appropriately catches that error. However, I think I should focus on catching `MockitoException` specifically, instead of the broader `RuntimeException` that comes from defining modules. \n\nIf the native dynamic compiler throws an `UnsupportedOperationException`, that’s not the intended error type, so it would fail. I also wonder if I need to avoid direct reflection in this context.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0c6114a654385776016a05f29ce